[11] Media report 25 Apr 2014 - 1 case Taiwan ex Mainland China
Date: 25 Apr 2014
Source: Focus Taiwan [edited]
http://focustaiwan.tw/news/asoc/201404250028.aspx


Taiwan's Centers for Disease Control (CDC) confirmed Friday [25 Apr 2014] the island's 4th imported case of H7N9 avian flu since April last year [2013].

The patient, a 39-year-old Taiwanese businessman, developed symptoms similar to that of H7N9 when he entered Taiwan on [19 Apr 2014], after traveling to Beijing and Kunshan in eastern China. X-ray test results on [23 Apr 2014] showed that he had pulmonary infiltration. He was then sent to a hospital for intensive care, the CDC said. The case was confirmed to be H7N9 at 6 p.m. Friday [25 Apr 2014]

Initial investigation found that the patient had neither contact with birds nor had visited markets where live poultry was sold when he was in China, according to the CDC.

People who have had close contact with the patient, including 3 family members and one colleague, did not develop suspicious symptoms, the CDC said. CDC officials said they are also keeping track of a total of 57 medical personnel who have come in contact with the patient, as well as 8 passengers who were on the same flight with him.

The CDC is currently in the process of reporting the case to the World Health Organization.

Friday's [25 Apr 2014] case was the 2nd H7N9 patient identified in Taiwan this week. A 44-year-old tourist from China's Jiangsu Province was found to be infected with the disease on Tuesday [22 Apr 2014].

Taiwan confirmed its 1st and 2nd imported H7N9 cases from China on [24 Apr 2013 and 31 Dec 2013], respectively.

Since [3 Apr 2013], a total of 581 suspected H7N9 cases have been reported in Taiwan, but only 4 have been confirmed, with the December [2013] case proving fatal. All the other cases tested negative.

[Byline: Lee Hsin-Yin]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail from HealthMap Alerts
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Since the last ProMED update on the avian influenza A(H7N9) situation in China, there have been a total of 9 newly diagnosed cases of infection related to exposure on mainland China. Noteworthy is that of the 7 new cases reported by WHO, only one mentions that there was a prior history of exposure to live poultry (note that a media report on another case did mention that the case had purchased and slaughtered a live chicken in Jiangsu prior to onset of symptoms). Are these new cases from person-to-person contact, or was there live poultry exposure that wasn't mentioned by the patient or family members upon questioning or not reported to official channels?

Overall, it appears as though transmission may be slowing down. It also appears as though transmission has significantly slowed down in Zhejiang and Guangdong, the 2 provinces with previously the highest numbers of cases, but it may be picking up in Jiangsu (5 of the 9 newly reported cases had exposure in Jiangsu.

For a map of China showing provinces, see http://www.sacu.org/maps/provmap.png. The HealthMap/ProMED map of China can be found at https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=2432943,155. - Mod.MPP]
